      "strengths_deep_dive": [
        "Sadagaat-USA's operational model is characterized by its lean administrative structure and direct service delivery. By maintaining <cite id=\"12\">100% independent board members</cite>, the organization ensures objective oversight of its <cite id=\"1\">five major program sectors</cite>. Their financial resilience is evidenced by <cite id=\"13\">3.6 months of working capital</cite>, which provides a stable foundation for long-term projects in volatile regions like Sudan. Furthermore, the organization has successfully scaled its impact, as seen in its <cite id=\"14\">$980,000 in foreign grants</cite> distributed to support international humanitarian relief."
      ],
      "summary": "founded in 2002, Sadagaat-USA is a humanitarian organization dedicated to alleviating poverty and improving essential services for marginalized communities, primarily in Sudan and the United States. The organization operates through a multi-sectoral approach, managing high-impact programs in <cite id=\"1\">education, health, feeding, and water sectors</cite>. Sadagaat-USA distinguishes itself through extreme financial efficiency, reporting a <cite id=\"2\">98.4% program expense ratio</cite> in its most recent filings, ensuring that donor contributions are directed almost entirely to frontline services. The organization maintains a <cite id=\"3\">perfect 100 score for Culture & Accountability</cite> from Charity Navigator, reflecting a deep commitment to organizational transparency and ethical leadership. With <cite id=\"4\">$1,294,453 in total revenue</cite> for the 2023 tax year, the charity has demonstrated significant growth, achieving a <cite id=\"5\">33.4% three-year revenue CAGR</cite>. Their educational initiatives are particularly specialized, focusing on <cite id=\"6\">marginalized groups such as the blind</cite> and children who have been excluded from formal schooling. As a <cite id=\"7\">zakat-eligible entity</cite>, Sadagaat-USA provides a verified channel for Muslim donors to fulfill their religious obligations through projects that serve the <cite id=\"8\">fuqara (poor) and masakin (needy)</cite> in high-urgency regions.",
